From: jdahl@rchland.vnet.ibm.com (Jared Dahl)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: Thu, 19 Aug 1993 20:43:20 GMT

In article <CC0qx4.4D@news2.cis.umn.edu>, virus@orca.micro.umn.edu (Tom Maki) writes:
|> 
|> >For Immdediate Release: NT versus Linux, a feature comparison
|> >-------------------------------------------------------------
|> 
|> >Feature                     NT                          Linux
|> >-------                     --                          -----
|> 
|> >microkernel                 yes                         no (monolethic)
|> >kernel size                 50k                         350k
|> >loadable device
|> >drivers                     yes                         no
|> >true dynamic link
|> >libraries (DLL)             yes                         no
|> >per-application DLLs        yes                         no
|> >integrated GUI              yes                         no (add-on)

NT has only ONE GUI and will never have another, while
X may change and improve or be replaced.

|> >drag and drop               yes                         no
|> >DDE support                 yes                         no
|> >max chars in file name      unlimited                   14

WRONG.  EXT2 filesystem is not limited to 14 characters.

|> >max partition size          unlimited                   64MB

WRONG.  EXT2 filesystem is not limited to 64mb.

|> >C2 securiy                  yes                         no
|> >memory model                flat                        internally segmented
|> >protable                    yes                         no (x86 only)

Linux is being developed for Amiga, Mac, and MCA bus.

|> >runs unix apps              yes (source level)          yes (source level)
|> >runs DOS apps               yes                         no

Ever heard of dosemu?

|> >runs Windows apps           yes                         no

Who knows?  Someday soon, WABI should work.

|> >max addressable mem         2048 Gig                    4 Gig
|> >multimedia support          yes                         no
|> >QIC-80 support              yes                         no
|> >min required mem            12 meg                      16 meg (w/ X)

I run 4 megs and X(while slow) is good for testing development
work.  I am currently learning Xt programming with Linux.

Besides, if you are strapped for money, what is better than a 
GUI that is $free$ and needs only 4 megs to run?

|> >min required disk space     60 meg                      120 meg (all series)

I run Linux with 70 meg, and have a full featured UNIX.  

|> >networking                  stable                      unstable
|> >price                       $110 (educational)          $69 (SLS)

LINUX IS FREELY AVAILABLE THROUGH FTP AND IS EASY TO GET.
What is the non-educational price of NT?  How does that compare
to $0?

Heres a couple categories this person left out:

                               NT                     Linux                      
                               __                     _____
source code provided           NO                       YES

GNU compatible development      ?                       YES
  environment

profits go to                  Bill Gates             No One

figure head                    Bill Gates             Linus Torvalds

upgrade cost                   Big $$$                FREE!!!

cost if you decide that        Big $$$                FREE!!!
  you don't like it

number of developers working   thousands              hundreds
  on this                      (full time)            (part time)

can it be installed on your    NO!!!!                 YES
  machine today?


|> Though this is really comparing apples and oranges, I wonder if any
|> linux advocates would care to correct this disinformation?

Yes.  It may be a fair comparison if there were thousands of 
paid programmers working for years to write Linux.  

Someone else get the rest of these.  Let's avoid addressing his
claims about NT, but instead address his incorrect claims about
Linux.  I'm sure there are people who would delight to see these
groups shut down by holy wars over NT.

